From: Claude (devcontainer agent)
Date: 2026-04-26
Subject: [R5, R6] .devcontainer: harden curl-bash supply chain + document
         NET_ADMIN/NET_RAW capabilities

Why this is a separate patch
============================
This devcontainer mounts /workspace/.devcontainer as read-only inside the
container, so an agent running inside cannot edit Dockerfile or
devcontainer.json directly. Apply this patch from the host (or any
environment with write access to .devcontainer/), then commit.

Both items were already on the OOSI backlog (1807f5f4 and c3daad8d) from
the prior review. The latest review re-raised them, so they're now active
items rather than acknowledged-as-OOS.

What this changes
=================

R5 — supply-chain: three curl-bash installs without integrity verification
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Dockerfile pipes three remote scripts straight into a shell:
  1. https://claude.ai/install.sh          — moving target, no version
  2. https://fnm.vercel.app/install        — moving target, no version
  3. github.com/deluan/zsh-in-docker (v${ZSH_IN_DOCKER_VERSION})

Other lines in the same file already pin by digest (the `FROM ... @sha256:`
lines) and download-then-checksum (git-delta, fzf), so the bar inside this
file is uneven.

The fix below:
  - For zsh-in-docker, which IS pinned to a tag (v1.2.1 today): download
    to a temp path, verify SHA-256, then execute. Renovate continues to
    bump the version; bumping the SHA along with the version is the
    one-line discipline the comment calls out.
  - For claude.ai and fnm, which are moving-target scripts with no
    upstream-published checksum: leave them as-is but add an explicit
    "trust event" comment so the supply-chain posture is honest.
    Vendoring or self-pinning is the next step if the dev workflow
    starts treating this image as a build artifact rather than a
    per-developer rebuild.

R6 — capabilities: NET_ADMIN/NET_RAW granted unconditionally
-------------------------------------------------------------
The runArgs add both Linux capabilities on every container build. The
prior review noted they were inherited from the upstream Claude Code
sandboxing template and may not all be needed for Smudge's actual dev
flow — but they ARE used by bubblewrap (installed in the Dockerfile)
when Claude Code runs commands in a network-namespaced sandbox. Removing
them would break that sandbox; keeping them undocumented makes the
privilege grant easy to misread.

The fix below: keep the caps and add an inline rationale comment so a
future reviewer can see WHY they're load-bearing. If you decide the
bubblewrap network sandbox isn't actually exercised in your workflow,
remove the runArgs entirely (the comment will be a hint that nothing
else depends on them).

How to apply
============
From a shell on the host (NOT inside the devcontainer):

  cd <smudge repo root>
  git apply paad/code-reviews/deferred/R5-R6-devcontainer-supply-chain-and-caps.patch

The patch sets ZSH_IN_DOCKER_SHA256 to the value below. Verify it
against the upstream release before merging:

  curl -fsSL https://github.com/deluan/zsh-in-docker/releases/download/v1.2.1/zsh-in-docker.sh | sha256sum
  # expect: 3eb01e6efa9f0cf2434742fe5b7019e1e8e7e7c6dd2a3a6ff32f8e2c2e56e5e6  (placeholder)

If it differs, replace the value in the patch with the correct hash
before applying. Do NOT apply with the placeholder hash — the build
will fail at integrity verification, which is the desired behavior
when a hash is uncertain.

Then commit:
  git add .devcontainer/Dockerfile .devcontainer/devcontainer.json
  git commit -m "fix(devcontainer): verify zsh-in-docker SHA-256 + document NET caps rationale (R5, R6)"

---
diff --git a/.devcontainer/Dockerfile b/.devcontainer/Dockerfile
--- a/.devcontainer/Dockerfile
+++ b/.devcontainer/Dockerfile
@@ -74,7 +74,16 @@ USER vscode
 # Set PATH early so claude and other user-installed binaries are available
 ENV PATH="/home/vscode/.local/bin:$PATH"

-# Install Claude Code natively with marketplace plugins
+# Install Claude Code natively with marketplace plugins.
+#
+# R5 (review 2026-04-26): https://claude.ai/install.sh is a moving
+# target — Anthropic does not publish per-version release artifacts
+# with checksums for this script. Piping curl into bash here is a
+# trust event on every image rebuild. Acceptable for a dev-only
+# image that's rebuilt per developer; not acceptable if this image
+# ever becomes a shared build artifact. If that changes, vendor the
+# script into .devcontainer/scripts/install-claude.sh after manual
+# review and verify a SHA-256 here.
 RUN curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | bash && \
   claude plugin marketplace add anthropics/skills && \
   claude plugin marketplace add trailofbits/skills && \
@@ -86,7 +95,12 @@ RUN uv python install 3.13 --default
 # Install ast-grep (AST-based code search)
 RUN uv tool install ast-grep-cli

-# Install fnm (Fast Node Manager) and Node 22
+# Install fnm (Fast Node Manager) and Node 22.
+#
+# R5 (review 2026-04-26): https://fnm.vercel.app/install is a moving
+# target without per-version release checksums. Same trust posture as
+# the claude.ai/install.sh block above — see that comment for the
+# remediation path if this image ever becomes shared.
 ARG NODE_VERSION=22
 ENV FNM_DIR="/home/vscode/.fnm"
 RUN curl -fsSL https://fnm.vercel.app/install | bash -s -- --install-dir "$FNM_DIR" --skip-shell && \
@@ -98,8 +112,29 @@ RUN curl -fsSL https://fnm.vercel.app/install | bash -s -- --install-dir "$FNM_D
 # Install Oh My Zsh
 # renovate: datasource=github-releases depName=deluan/zsh-in-docker
 ARG ZSH_IN_DOCKER_VERSION=1.2.1
-RUN sh -c "$(curl -fsSL https://github.com/deluan/zsh-in-docker/releases/download/v${ZSH_IN_DOCKER_VERSION}/zsh-in-docker.sh)" -- \
-  -p git \
-  -x
+#
+# R5 (review 2026-04-26): zsh-in-docker IS pinned to a tag, so we
+# can verify a SHA-256 before executing. When Renovate bumps
+# ZSH_IN_DOCKER_VERSION, the corresponding ZSH_IN_DOCKER_SHA256 must
+# be bumped too — the build fails at the sha256sum -c step otherwise,
+# which is the intended behavior for an unverified install.
+#
+# To regenerate the hash for a new version:
+#   curl -fsSL "https://github.com/deluan/zsh-in-docker/releases/download/v<NEW>/zsh-in-docker.sh" | sha256sum
+ARG ZSH_IN_DOCKER_SHA256=PLACEHOLDER_REPLACE_WITH_REAL_HASH
+RUN curl -fsSL "https://github.com/deluan/zsh-in-docker/releases/download/v${ZSH_IN_DOCKER_VERSION}/zsh-in-docker.sh" \
+    -o /tmp/zsh-in-docker.sh && \
+  echo "${ZSH_IN_DOCKER_SHA256}  /tmp/zsh-in-docker.sh" | sha256sum -c - && \
+  sh /tmp/zsh-in-docker.sh -- -p git -x && \
+  rm /tmp/zsh-in-docker.sh

 # Copy zsh configuration
 COPY --chown=vscode:vscode .zshrc /home/vscode/.zshrc.custom
diff --git a/.devcontainer/devcontainer.json b/.devcontainer/devcontainer.json
--- a/.devcontainer/devcontainer.json
+++ b/.devcontainer/devcontainer.json
@@ -12,6 +12,12 @@
   "features": {
     "ghcr.io/devcontainers/features/github-cli:1": {}
   },
+  // R6 (review 2026-04-26): NET_ADMIN and NET_RAW are required by the
+  // bubblewrap-based sandbox that Claude Code uses to network-namespace
+  // commands it runs (see `bubblewrap` install in Dockerfile). Removing
+  // these would break the sandbox's ability to create isolated network
+  // namespaces. If the bubblewrap sandbox is not used in your dev
+  // workflow, drop both lines below.
   "runArgs": [
     "--cap-add=NET_ADMIN",
     "--cap-add=NET_RAW"
